fields.title: How to register your own company in India from USA
fields.Short_des: With the advent of globalisation, connectivity worldwide has become the sole propeller for international co-operation and belongingness. This journey from a national company to an international company has now been seen as the success marker of so many companies. With the compliance of specific rules and necessary steps involved in the procedure, this has become achievable with, of course, your visionary mindset!
fields.content:
Let’s jump right into some steps involved with the registration:

First, decide for the type of business that you want to venture for a sole proprietorship, one person company (OPC), partnership, co-operative.

This will help you to set a specific direction that you need to work in, thus reducing the various options you need to choose from.

Some initial conditions you need to fulfil-

At least one Indian resident needed as the director 

Must have is all the required documents and KYC details. Ensure the notarization and attestation of all the documents from the respective departments of the respective ministries. The list of documents needed for registration are as follows:

  • Copy of your passport (valid passport)
  • Copy of driving license from the issuing country
  • Voter ID
  • Photos
  • Residential permit (issued by the respective embassy)
  • Valid business visa 
  • Social security number- a 9-digit number in the format AAA-GG-SSS can be used as a valid proof of identification. To determine social security benefit.
  • Ensure the foreign direct investments details for the company- automatic route for FDIs do not require prior permission from the associated ministry or even reserve bank of India (RBI).
  • Certificate of authentication (needed when you wish to open any bank account in the country of business)
  • Certificate of appropriation (needed to prove that the company has been legally incorporated)
  • Valid address proof (residential address)
  • After creating a user account in the ministry of corporate affairs:
  1. Apply for the DSC (digital signature certificate).
  2. Get DSC done by the certified authorities with the needed valid documents.
  3. After signing in the MINISTRY OF CORPORATE AFFAIRS PORTAL, apply for the name of the company. After the uniqueness of the name is certified, your company name is authorized, giving way to the certification of incorporation.

After the above steps, the certificate of the corporation in India received your company is finally registered! This ensures the formation of your company in India.

DIN was introduced newly with the insertion of 266A-266G of COMPANIES (AMENDMENT) ACT, 2006. For the Director identification number (DIN) to be received, you need to fill up the SPICE FORM. The details of the director need to be elaborately specified with attached valid documents of proof.

The above steps can help you enable a strong foothold in a business company other than your own country. So, let’s take this global initiative a notch up by indulging in inter-country business. All the best!

fields.title: Understanding the concept of LLP and its tax implications
fields.Short_des: Identified under Income Tax Act, 1961 section 2(23) both firm and LLP get the same status under the Indian Partnership Act, 1932. LLP (limited liability partnership) being a separate legal entity in our country is considerably taxable just like any other company. Defined under the Limited Partnership Act,2008 it is a corporate body. Henceforth, the LLP taxation remains the same as for the firm in India.
fields.content:
Characteristics of LLP

FORM 1: LLP name approval

FORM 2: submit for incorporation

FORM 3: LLP agreement

FORM 4: partner consent

FORM 7: DSC & DIN number

FORM 8: submit statement of account & solvency within one month from FY closure

FORM 11: annual return with registrar within two months from the FY closure

LLP Tax Structure

  • With TDS (tax deducted at source) in operation things have since then been quite easier to deal with.
  • Taxed 30% with an additional surcharge and cess:

30% + 2% (education cess) +1%(secondary, higher education) + 10%(surcharge, if income exceeds INR 1 crore)

  • With 2020-2021 revised estimates of surcharge is 12%, education cess of 4% is payable along with the surcharge.
  • LLP engaged in supplying goods and services have to get themselves registered under GST if their total turnover is more than INR 20 lakhs in a year.
  • On income <+ 1 crore (31.20%), income > 1 crore (34.32%)
  • No double taxation intended.
  • Foreign investments are restrictive comparatively (except where 100% FDI is allowed via automatic route.
  • Dividend distribution tax (DDT) payable by the company on distribution of dividend is approximated to about 17% on profits and 20.5% on the amount of dividend.
  • Tax on receipt of dividend (TRD) is approximately equal to 8% for a resident non-corporate shareholder on receipt.
  • Alternate minimum taxation (AMT) is a process via which companies claim for certain exemptions in their taxation. It was specifically introduced only for the companies trying to encourage for more tax inclusion. AMT can be charged at the rate of 18.50% with an additional cess and surcharge levied on the income.

AMT at the rate of 9% is levied with an additional cess and surcharge in case of a non-corporate unit.AMT can be used only in case of adjusted total income exceeds the amount INR 20 lakhs.AMT can only be availed by the entities as mentioned in the sections specifically.

  • To claim for partner remuneration a clear clause must be specified in the LLP agreement- stating the allowance or payment of remuneration/interest payable on the loan and capital provided by the partners.
  • The deduction of remuneration can happen in following ways-
    • LLP payment to partner
    • LLP with income tax surcharge
    • LLP with tax return filing (signed by the designated partners)

With certain powers comes certain responsibilities and we hope that this powerful decision of business venture you come out as a strong and reliable company. The above summation of LLP’s taxation structure, will hopefully get you to venture into your own dream business.

fields.title: Points to remember while proposing the name of the company/LLP.
fields.Short_des: Proposal and approval of name is one of the most important concern while incorporating any entity.
fields.content:
Proposal and approval of name is one of the most important concern while incorporating any entity.

 

The name should be:

  • Unique and different 
  • Reflect the aim and objectives 
  • In line with Company Name Guidelines issued by MCA

The name should not be:

  • Similar, Identical, Phonetical or resembling to name of existing company or LLP.
  • Similar to registered or applied trademark
  • Offensive under any law
  • having any word or expression which is likely to give the impression that the company is in any way connected to the government central or state or any other local authority when it is actually not unless the approval from the respective government authority has been attained

                       Once the name is proposed, check if the similar name or trademark is not available through the name and trademark search on MCA port

fields.title: Difference between DIN and DPIN.
fields.Short_des: Most of the time DIN and DPIN are used interchangeably. But there are few differences between them. Lets discuss them-
fields.content:
Most of the time DIN and DPIN are used interchangeably. But there are few differences between them. Let’s discuss them-

  • DIN stands for Director Identification Number whereas DPIN stands for Designated Partner Identification number.
  • DIN is universal. You don’t need to apply for DPIN if you already have DIN. Even if you want to be a designated partner, you can apply for DIN instead of applying for DPIN. 
  • A person with DPIN can not be a director in a company. To be a director in a company, DIN is required.
  • If you have both DIN and DPIN, then DPIN stands cancel.

fields.title: Public Limited Company
fields.Short_des: As per Companies Act 2013, a Public Limited Company is a company that has limited liability and may offer shares to the general public by Initial Public Offer
fields.content:
• Definition: 

As per Companies Act 2013, a Public Limited Company is a company that has limited liability and may offer shares to the general public by Initial Public Offer (IPO). Where the company is listed, an individual can also acquire the shares of such company through stock market. It has stringent regulatory requirements and no exemption has been allowed under the Companies Act 2013.

  • Features of Public Limited Company
  1. Limited Liability: This means shareholders of the company are not liable to pay any amount over and above the unpaid amount on shares hold by them at the time of liquidation.
  2. Directors and their Appointment: Section 149 of the Companies Act, 2013 states that a Public Limited company shall have a minimum of 3 directors. Further, a company can have a maximum number of 15 directors. However, through a special resolution a company may appoint more than the prescribed limit.
  3. Paid-up Capital: A public limited company shall have a minimum paid-up capital of 5 Lacs INR or such higher amount as may be prescribed under the act.
  4. Name of the company: As per Companies Act 2013, any company which has registered as Public Ltd. A company is required to add the word ‘limited’ after their name.
  5. Prospectus: As per Section 2(70) of the Companies Act 2013, a prospectus means any documents including red-herring and shelf prospectus or any notices, circular, advertisement, or other documents that are issued by the company for inviting offer from the public for the subscription of shares or debentures.

fields.heading1_details: Sole proprietorship is a form of business entity managed by a single owner who is personally liable for the profits & losses of the company. It is the simplest form of business entity with minimal compliance requirements. There is no as such registration required for sole proprietorship as anyone can easily start this business with no formalities and few compliance requirements. In case you are not having enough cash in your hands but you still want to start your own proprietary firm or proprietary company, you can easily go with this option. This form of business entity is especially popular among small traders and merchants. Liability for this form of business entity is unlimited and doesn’t have perpetual existence.
fields.heading2: Why Sole Proprietorship is Popular in India?
fields.heading2_details:
Sole proprietorship is a popular form of business now days and many business entrepreneurs prefer them over other forms of business because of the following reasons –

  • Sole proprietorship is one of the oldest and simplest business structures that a business owner can handle single handedly.
  • Simple business form to start with and close.
  • Flexibility in carrying out business activities.
  • Very economical as compared to other forms of business entity.
  • It has minimal compliance requirements.
  • You are the only decision maker – Not answerable to anybody and independent to give instructions and orders.
  • No tension of sharing income & profits with anyone.
  • Only you are responsible for the profits you earn and losses you incurred.

  • E-commerce or internet based business.
  • Trader/Retailer/Aggregator/Manufacturer – You are among any of them.
  • If you are having turnover of Rs.20 Lakh within a state.

fields.content: Absolutely not. Registration of a company is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone.

fields.heading: What is Private Ltd Company?
fields.content: Section 2(68) of Companies Act, 2013 defines private companies. According to that, private companies are those companies whose articles of association restrict the transferability of shares and prevent the public at large from subscribing to them. This is the basic criterion that differentiates private companies from public companies.

fields.heading: Minimum requirements to form a Private Ltd Company?
fields.content: A unique name, minimum of 2 shareholders, minimum of two directors,  Capital to invest, Requisite documents and MOA & AOA

fields.heading: What is DSC? Who shall obtain DSC?
fields.content: The Information Technology Act, 2000 has provisions for use of Digital Signatures on the documents submitted in electronic form in order to ensure the security and authenticity of the documents filed electronically. This is secure and authentic way to submit a document electronically. The directors and subscribers of the company should obtain DSC (Digital signature certificate), as absence of DSC can cause site related problems to the website visitors and subscribers.

fields.heading: How to obtain a DSC?
fields.content:
• Digital Signature Certificate (DSC) Applicants can directly approach Certifying Authorities (CAs) with original supporting documents, and self-attested copies will be sufficient in this case
• DSCs can also be obtained, wherever offered by CA, using Aadhar eKYC based authentication, and supporting documents are not required in this case
• A letter/certificate issued by a Bank containing the DSC applicant’s information as retained in the Bank database can be accepted. Such letter/certificate should be certified by the Bank Manager

fields.heading: Which class of DSC should I obtain?
fields.content: The Ministry of Corporate Affairs has stipulated a Class-II or above category signing certificate for e-Filings under MCA21. A person who already has the specified DSC for any other application can use the same for filings under MCA21 and is not required to obtain a fresh DSC.

fields.heading: What are the minimum and maximum number of members in a Private company?
fields.content: Private companies can have minimum of 2 members and maximum of 200 members.

fields.heading: What is the minimum expenditure for operating a Private Ltd Company?
fields.content: The expense of managing a private limited company is usually divided into 4 categories: expense of establishing a private limited business, price of accounting and auditing, cost of miscellaneous expenses and compliances. You have to spend minimum Rs.40000 in every cost category.

fields.heading: Can LLP be converted into Private Limited Company?
fields.content: Unfortunately no, conversion of an LLP into a Private Limited Company is not possible. The LLP Act, 2008 and the Companies Act, 2013, do not have any any provision related to conversion. If one desires to have the same name that of a LLP, then they have to incorporate a brand new Private Limited Company  and LLP Company has to issue a no objection certification (NOC) for it.

fields.heading: Who can act as a member of OPC?
fields.content: Only an individual who is an Indian citizen and resident in India shall be eligible to act as a member and nominee of an OPC. For the above purpose, the term “resident in India” means a person who has stayed in India for a period of not less than one hundred and eighty-two days during the immediately preceding one financial year.

fields.heading: What is the minimum capital required for registration of sole proprietorship firm?

fields.heading: Is it possible to convert a proprietorship firm into a private limited company, partnership firm, LLP etc.?
fields.content: Yes, it is possible to convert a proprietorship firm into private limited company, partnership or an LLP. This process is little bit complex but it is still possible.

fields.heading: How can I transfer my Proprietorship firm?
fields.content: A proprietorship business cannot be transferred to another person unlike private limited company or an LLP. You can transfer the assets of proprietary firm to another person by sale but intangible assets like registrations; government approvals etc. cannot be transferred.

fields.heading: Who can start a Sole Proprietorship Business?
fields.content: Any individual with current account in the name of his business can start a sole proprietorship firm. In order to open a bank account, Shops & Establishment registration is required by bank.

fields.heading: How long does it take to start a sole proprietorship business?
fields.content: Any individual can start a sole proprietorship business within 15 days. It is specifically started by small traders & merchants because of its cheap cost.

fields.heading: Can I apply for sole proprietorship registration online?
fields.content: Yes, you can apply for sole proprietorship registration online with Finacbooks.

fields.heading: Whether I can convert sole proprietorship firm into private limited company or partnership firm?
fields.content: Yes, you can convert sole proprietorship firm into private limited company or partnership firm. The procedure is bit long but it is possible. Many sole proprietors convert their proprietorship firm into partnership firm or a private limited company at a later stage.

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for Registration of Section 8 Company?
fields.content: Absolutely not. Registration of a company is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone.

fields.heading: Minimum requirements of Registering a section 8 company?
fields.content:
1. An Individual or HUF or limited Company is eligible to register as section 8 companies in India.
  2. Minimum 2 directors and 2 members are required to register section 8 company.
  3. Two or more person who will act as a shareholder or Director of the company should fulfil all the requirements and compliances of the Section 8 Company registration.
  4. At least one of the directors shall be a resident of India. However, a firm may be a member of the company registered under this section.
  5. The purpose should be the promotion of sports, social welfare, the advancement of science and art, education and financial assistance to lower income groups etc.
  6. The surplus gained must be utilized for meeting the principal objective of the section 8 company only.
  7. Founders, members, and directors of the company cannot draw any remuneration in any form of cash or kind.
  8. No profit should be distributed among the members and director of the company directly or indirectly
  9. The company should have the clear vision, goals and project plan for the next three years.

fields.heading: Do section 8 company need to get approval from Central Government?
fields.content: Yes, prior to registration you need to get approval from Central Government.

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for PT Registration?
fields.content: Absolutely not. PT Registration is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone

fields.heading: Is PT Registration Mandatory?
fields.content: Employers are required to deduct and deposit taxes from employees whose pay exceeds the minimum slab limit. That entity must get a registration certificate as well as an enrolment certificate

fields.heading: When to get a PT Registration Certificate?
fields.content: The company/firm must have a professional tax registration certificate (PTRC) within 30 days of employing a staff member. The employers are supposed to deduct professional tax from the salary of their employees and submit it at the professional tax department during the time of filing returns.

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for GST Registration?
fields.content: Absolutely not. GST Registration is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone

fields.heading: Is GST registration mandatory for every organisation?
fields.content: No, GST registration is mandatory for the organisation who are specifically mentioned under the GST Act and the organisations whose turnover has exceeded the threshold limit ie RS 40 lakhs

fields.heading: What is the validity of GSTIN?
fields.content: GSTIN is valid for lifetime.

fields.heading: Who can opt for Composition scheme under GST?
fields.content:
Small taxpayers who wish to have lesser compliances to deal with and lower rates of taxes under GST, can opt for the Composition scheme,

                         A trader whose aggregate turnover is below Rs 1.5 crore can opt for the Composition scheme. In the case of North-Eastern states and Himachal Pradesh, the present limit is Rs.75 lakh. 

Also, the government extended the Composition scheme to service providers having an aggregate turnover of up to Rs.50 lakh.

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for TAN Registration?
fields.content: Absolutely not. TAN Registration is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone

fields.heading: Is TAN registration mandatory for every organisation?
fields.content: No, TAN registration is mandatory for the organisation who has to either deduct or collect the tax and file the TDS and TCS return.

fields.heading: What is the validity of TAN?
fields.content: TAN is valid for lifetime.

fields.heading: Why is it necessary to have TAN?
fields.content: TAN is required to be quoted in all TDS/TCS returns, all TDS/TCS payment challans and all TDS/TCS certificates to be issued. TDS/TCS returns will not be received if TAN is not quoted and challans for TDS/TCS payments will not be accepted by banks. Failure to apply for TAN or not quoting the same in the specified documents attracts a penalty of Rs. 10,000/.

fields.heading: Who needs TAN?
fields.content: Anybody who is liable to deduct or collect the tax at source needs to have a TAN card.

fields.heading: Can TDS or TCS return be filed without TDS?
fields.content: No, it is mandatory to mention TAN while filing the returns.

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for Registration of Company?
fields.content: Absolutely not. Registration of a company is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone

fields.heading: Minimum Requirements for registration of Public limited company.
fields.content:
• Minimum 3 directors
  • Minimum 7 shareholders
  • DIN for all directors
  • Minimum capital of Rs. 5 Lacs

fields.heading: Who can become a director in a Public Ltd Company ?
fields.content: The director needs to be atleast 18 years of age. Any individual can become the member including foreigners/NRIs

fields.heading: Statutory Compliances for Public Limited Company?
fields.content: A public Company must hold a Board Meeting at least once in every 3 Month. Additionally, an AGM must be conducted at least once a year.

fields.heading: Why to chose Public Limited Company ?
fields.content:
• Shares can be transferred and that too quickly
  • High borrowing capacity
  • Listing shares on exchange
  • Liability is limited
  • Separate Legal Entity

fields.heading: Annual compliances to be followed by section 8 companies?
fields.content:
1. Atleast two board meeting during a year
  2. Annual returns to be filed
  3. Book keeping
  4. Mandatory Audit
  5. ITR filing
  6. Additional compliances as stated by the authorities.

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for Societys Registration?
fields.content: Absolutely not. Society’s Registration is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone

fields.heading: Minimum number of members required for registration of a society?
fields.content: 7 Members

fields.heading: Is it mandatory to register a society?
fields.content: No, it is recommendatory to get your society register to enjoy all the benefits like exemption from taxes.

fields.heading: Mandatory Compliances for an OPC to be fulfilled.
fields.content:
1. At least one Board Meeting in each half of the calendar year and the time gap between the two Board Meetings should not be less than 90 days.
  2. Maintenance of books of accounts
  3. Audit of Financial Statements 
  4. Filing income tax return
  5. Filing of financial statements with ROC

fields.heading: Can a foreigner/NRI form an OPC?
fields.content: No

fields.heading: Mandatory conditions where OPC has to get converted either into private or public company.
fields.content: In case the paid-up share capital of an OPC exceeds fifty lakh rupees or its average annual turnover of immediately preceding three consecutive financial years exceeds two crore rupees, then the OPC has to mandatorily convert itself into a private or public company.

fields.heading: Why OPC?
fields.content:
1. Limited liability of Director
  2. Easy to raise funds and loans
  3. Complete Control
  4. Easy to less as documentation is very less
  5. Conversion is possible
  6. Better credibility in market
  7. Lesser compliances as compared to other form of companies.

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for Registration of Nidhi Company?
fields.content: Absolutely not. Registration of a company is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone.

fields.heading: Minimum requirements of Registering before a Nidhi company?
fields.content:
1. Minimum number of shareholders or members – 7
  2. Minimum number of Directors -3
  3. The minimum capital requirement is of Rs. 5 lakhs
  4. DIN for Directors
  5. Minimum 3 Directors.
  6. No Preference Shares shall be issued.
  7. The objective of the company shall be to cultivate the habit of saving by “receiving deposits” from and “lending to” it’s members only for their mutual benefit.

fields.heading: Minimum post registration requirement of a Nidhi Company
fields.content:
1. By the end of the 1st year, the number of members or shareholders of the Nidhi Company must be at least 200.
  2. Net owned fund should be more than Rs. 10 lakhs.
  3. The ratio for NOF to Deposit should be more than 1:20.
  4. Unencumbered deposits should exceed 10 % of outstanding deposits.

fields.heading: Do nidhi company need to get approval from RBI?
fields.content: No

fields.heading: Can a Nidhi company buy securities of another company?
fields.content: No

fields.heading: Can a Nidhi company issue unsecured loans?
fields.content: No, only secured loan.

fields.heading: Do I need to obtain multiple GSTIN if my business operates in multiple places?
fields.content: Yes, you need to get multiple GSTIN if your business operates in different states. But, if it operates in the same state then there is no need to get multiple GSTIN.

fields.heading: Can I modify the details after registration?
fields.content: Yes

fields.heading: Is it possible to cancel the GST registration?
fields.content: Yes

fields.heading: Do I need to visit the office or any other Government Regulated body for the License?
fields.content: Absolutely not. This is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone.

fields.heading: Who can be the applicants of PSARA License?
fields.content: Anybody who is indulged in the business of food related item/s.

fields.heading: What are the types of food license?
fields.content:
1. Basic FSSAI Registration - Annual turnover of less than Rs. 12 Lakhs
  2. State FSSAI License - Annual turnover between Rs. 12 Lakhs - Rs. 20 Crores
  3. Central FSSAI License - Annual turnover more than Rs. 20 Crores

fields.heading: Validity of Food License
fields.content: The FSSAI FoSCos License is valid for the period from 1 to 5 years. Hereafter, the particular FBO needs to apply for FSSAI License renewal.

fields.content: Absolutely not. Partnership Registration is an online process. You just need to upload the documents on our website from your comfort zone

fields.heading: Minimum requirements for registering a partnership firm.
fields.content:
1. Partnership Agreement/Deed
  2. Minimum 2 partners
  3. Maximum 20 partners
  4. Capital investment
  5. Principal place of business
  6. PAN and Bank Account of the firm

fields.heading: Who can be the partner?
fields.content: An individual who is resident of India only can become the partner in a partnership firm

fields.heading: Benefits of registering a partnership firm
fields.content:
1. Power to file a case in a court by a partner against the firm or other co-partners.
  2. Power to file a case in court by the firm against third parties.

MSME stands for Micro, small & medium enterprises. As per the government, it is recommendatory to get registered under MSME, as it can provide you various benefits in the form of business set up, taxation, credit facilities, loans etc. Any enterprise involved in manufacturing or service sector can obtain registration under the MSME act. The Micro, Small and medium enterprise are defined below:

  • Micro Enterprise: Enterprises having investment less than Rs. 1 crore and turnover less than Rs. 5 crores are considered as Micro Enterprises.

Tax audits are the audit of books of account for certain individuals, businesses or companies as given under the provisions of Section 44AB. A tax audit comprises inspection of books with the aim of checking whether the income tax being filed are legitimate as per the Income Tax Act of 1961. The Income Tax Act of 1961 has many provisions for different types of audits, and there are various laws in place for various audits like cost audit, tax audit, statutory audit and company audit. Whether you fall in the category of people who need a compulsory tax audit or have been served a notice from the IRS to comply with a tax audit, there is nothing to panic about.

According to the Income Tax Act of 1961, certain taxpayers in business or profession are mandatorily required to file their tax audit report each year. Such a business/profession is subject to a tax audit in India only if the sales, turnover, or gross receipts exceed a certain threshold (INR 1 Crore) in a given financial year. As of FY 2020-21, this threshold has been proposed to be raised to INR 5 Crores given that the cash receipts and cash payments are limited to 5% of the turnover/gross receipts and gross payments respectively.

fields.heading: Can I file Income tax for previous period?
fields.content: Yes, a belated return is filed for a previous period with the penalty.

fields.heading: Who need to file ITR?
fields.content:
Every Indian including an NRI is required to file an Income tax return where Total Income exceeds the basic exemption limit of Rs. 2,50,000 for an individual; Rs. 3,00,000 in case of the senior citizen and Rs. 5,00,000 in case of the super senior citizen.

Total Income comprises income from all sources i.e. income from salary, house property, business income, capital gains or any other taxable income. This limit is to be checked before giving the benefit of deductions like 80C,80D, 80DDB etc. You are required to file a return irrespective of whether you have paid tax or not. So, even if the employer has deducted TDS in full you are still required to file an income tax return.

fields.heading: Applicability of IEC
fields.content: An IEC is necessary for the import/export of goods. In case the import/export is of services or technology, IEC is required in only limited circumstances, when import/export is in ‘specified services’ or ‘specified technologies’, i.e. services or technologies in which international trade is restricted by the Government of India as they pertain to national security, such as dealing in nuclear weapons, automatic guns, etc.

fields.heading: What is the validity of this certificate?
fields.content: IEC Certificate has a validity of lifetime.

fields.heading: Who need to get IEC certificate?
fields.content: Any person who does imports or exports or both for their business need to get IEC certificate

fields.heading: Is IEC mandatory?
fields.content: Yes. An Importer-Exporter Code (IEC) is a significant business identification number that is mandatory for import to India or export from India. A person/entity cannot export or import without obtaining an IEC unless specifically exempted.

fields.heading: Do I need to update my IEC profile annually?
fields.content: Yes. It is mandatory to update the IEC profile every year. In case of non-updation of the IEC profile, it will be deactivated. A deactivated IEC can be reactivated upon its successful updation. However, reactivation is subject to the condition that any other action should not be taken for violation of any provisions of the Foreign Trade Policy.
